					<marginalia_text>
						Iis solis studendum, eaq[ue] Sola curanda, qua[e] et per se
						sunt vtilissima:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						et virum efficiunt peritiorem; in summis scientijs profundiorem; in maximisq[ue]
						actionibus potentiorem. Prudentis est, vulgaria ista contemnere; omniaq[ue]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						spernere, qua[e]
						no[n] su[n]t in operando efficaciss[im]a.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Only in devoting onself to those things and only in carying for those things, which are most useful in themselves. 
				And they bring about a more experienced man, more profound in the highest sciences, and more powerful in the greats actions.
				It is the business of the prudent man to despise those common things and to scorn everything which is not most effective for acting.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
